@node "Features" "Features"

Features
--------

SmakeOpts has the following features:

- Runs as well from WB as from CLI (supported by tool types)

- Is able to run on a Public Screen

- uses a GUI created with @{"BGUI" link "BGUI"}

- includes example definition & rexx scripts for BED

- @{"BGUI" link "BGUI"} library included

- Source code included

@endnode

@node "Installation" "How to install the program"

Installation
------------

The installation of the program itself is quite simple. Just copy it to sc:c
or to another directory in your path if you use another one for external
SAS_C programs. The Guide should be copied to sc:help (I have sc:help in
my Amigaguide/Path, you need to add this if you wanna use the Online Help).

@{"BGUI.library" link "BGUI"} should be copied to LIBS:. This library is the newest beta
Version (V40.8) and if you're unsure about that you should get the BGUI
archive from Aminet (dev/gui) and install Version 39.

If you use BED as Editor you can as well add/change your SASC/C menu from
the SAS/C.dfn file. I only added this menu to the file and it contains one
new menu for the Options and the changed Build Project Menu. You also need
to copy the rewritten Build.bed (compatible to the old version) and the
SetSmakeOpts.bed  ARexx scripts to BED:rexx/SASC/.

Attention: I made more changes to the SAS/Menu than just the above mentioned.
I created some additional ARexx script (not in this archive) and sent them
to the author of BED, but they are not (yet ?) included with BED!

@endnode

@node "Requirements" "Requirements"

Requirements
------------

SmakeOpts needs the following requirement to work:

- An Amiga with at least 512 KB RAM (it should work, never testet it though)

- OS2.04 or better (I myself haven't tested it with OS2.04, because I only can
  use OS3.1, but I didn't use any 3.1 Features.)

- SAS/C 6.0 or higher (I have it only tested with SAS/C 6.56). I don't know if
  there are options which were added after release 6.0.

- @{"BGUI.library" link "BGUI"} V39 or higher (included in the archive). Only tested with V40.8

@endnode

@node "Usage" "Call from CLI/Workbench)"

Usage
-----

The usage from Workbench and CLI is principially the same. The names of the
CLI parameters are the same like the tool types, if you call it from the WB.

SmakeOpts 0.5 BETA 1. Copyright (C) 1996 Reinhard Katzmann. All rights reserved

USAGE: SmakeOpts P=PUBSCREEN/K

The PUBSCREEN keywords lets you open the Option program on another Public
Screen than Workbench.

Example:

> SmakeOpts PUBSCREEN=Blacks_Editor

This opens SmakeOpts on the Screen of BED.

After that you can edit your settings (see @{"GUI" link "GUI"}). If you save them
a file "smopts" will be created. This file will be read again with your
options if you call SmakeOpts next time.

smopts file
-----------

Now you have created your options you ask yourself how to use them. Smake
itself has no ENV-Variables itself for the configuration so I used alittle
trick in the OS (usually used for calling a filereq in CLI environment on
programs which don't have one):

> smake `type smopts`

Now smake is called with your configuration file (which actually contains
the parameters you defined with SmakeOpts before).

